1
00:01:05,455 --> 00:01:08,891
<i>[Music]</i>

2
00:01:26,855 --> 00:01:29,130
<i>Fay: I didn't come to
town To visit your aquarium</i>

3
00:01:29,375 --> 00:01:32,890
<i>I think a fish's place
Is in the sea</i>

4
00:01:33,095 --> 00:01:35,848
<i>I've heard you've got
A simply lovely planetarium</i>

5
00:01:36,055 --> 00:01:39,570
<i>But looking at the stars
Is not for me</i>

6
00:01:39,775 --> 00:01:42,573
<i>Now, don't drag me
Through your museum</i>

7
00:01:42,775 --> 00:01:46,609
<i>A picture postcard will do</i>

8
00:01:46,855 --> 00:01:50,814
<i>Don't give me souvenirs
I got no room to carry 'em</i>

9
00:01:51,015 --> 00:01:57,454
<i>The only souvenir I want is you</i>

10
00:01:57,655 --> 00:02:02,331
<i>I'm just a stranger in town</i>

11
00:02:02,535 --> 00:02:08,371
<i>And I've come down
For real hospitality</i>

12
00:02:08,575 --> 00:02:13,330
<i>Well, all right, then, baby, tonight</i>

13
00:02:13,535 --> 00:02:18,450
<i>Be good to a stranger in town</i>

14
00:02:19,735 --> 00:02:24,092
<i>I'm here to melt or to freeze</i>

15
00:02:24,295 --> 00:02:29,449
<i>In times like these
Let's skip the formality</i>

16
00:02:29,655 --> 00:02:36,208
<i>Baby, please
Be good to a stranger in town</i>

17
00:02:39,495 --> 00:02:42,646
Boy, is she sizzling tonight.
That don't help nobody.

18
00:02:42,855 --> 00:02:44,573
I bet you the notice goes up
come Saturday.

19
00:02:44,775 --> 00:02:46,493
Boy, you can smell this flop
clear to Times Square.

20
00:02:46,695 --> 00:02:49,892
Yeah, and in this theatre, too, where
Ferris and Lawrence had all their smashes.

21
00:02:50,135 --> 00:02:55,414
<i>Just help yourself
It is yours</i>

22
00:03:28,695 --> 00:03:32,324
<i>I'm just a stranger today</i>

23
00:03:32,535 --> 00:03:38,246
<i>But that's okay
A mere technicality</i>

24
00:03:38,455 --> 00:03:43,245
<i>Well, all right, tonight is tonight</i>

25
00:03:43,455 --> 00:03:48,290
<i>And, baby,
You're breaking me down</i>

26
00:03:48,495 --> 00:03:55,048
<i>So be good to a stranger in town</i>

27
00:03:58,975 --> 00:04:02,604
How's business tonight,
Mr Ferris? Terrible.

28
00:04:02,815 --> 00:04:06,091
I've been with you for more than ten
years, ever since you left Ziegfeld.

29
00:04:06,295 --> 00:04:08,968
I was with you that night in Minneapolis
when you saw Miss Lawrence for the first time

30
00:04:09,175 --> 00:04:10,813
at the old Orpheum.
Remember?

31
00:04:11,015 --> 00:04:12,971
You picked a fine time
to reminisce, Frank.

32
00:04:13,175 --> 00:04:14,767
I just wanted to say,
Mr Ferris,

33
00:04:14,975 --> 00:04:17,170
take advice of an old friend
and close Saturday.

34
00:04:17,375 --> 00:04:18,330
Not on your life.

35
00:04:18,535 --> 00:04:20,093
Tony Ferris may go down,
but not without a fight.

36
00:04:21,735 --> 00:04:23,771
Tell Mr Ferris I want to see him
in my dressing room.

37
00:04:23,975 --> 00:04:26,535
<i>Oui, madame.</i>

38
00:04:26,775 --> 00:04:29,050
Monsieur Ferris.
Yes?

39
00:04:29,295 --> 00:04:31,365
Miss Lawrence wants to see you
in her dressing room.

40
00:04:31,615 --> 00:04:35,130
All right.
Hold the fort.

41
00:04:37,215 --> 00:04:38,204
You sent for me, honey?

42
00:04:38,415 --> 00:04:40,531
I won't need you, Babette.

43
00:04:40,735 --> 00:04:43,169
You want to talk to me, Fay?
I don't, but it's necessary.

44
00:04:43,375 --> 00:04:45,809
Get that chair and sit down.

45
00:04:48,775 --> 00:04:50,766
<i>I want to talk
about Indiscretions,</i>

46
00:04:50,975 --> 00:04:52,533
and I don't mean my own.

47
00:04:52,775 --> 00:04:55,209
Well, go right ahead. I can always listen
to you with the greatest of pleasure.

48
00:04:55,455 --> 00:04:58,527
But you didn't listen when
I warned you about this show.

49
00:04:58,735 --> 00:05:00,771
Can't you see the way it's going,
it's no use?

50
00:05:00,975 --> 00:05:03,250
Why, if I stay with the show,
I'll lose my reputation.

51
00:05:03,495 --> 00:05:05,451
Well, I've been working on
some new promotion angles.

52
00:05:05,655 --> 00:05:07,566
<i>Fay, I can make another
Show Boat out of this.</i>

53
00:05:07,775 --> 00:05:09,288
Why, the idea's
cooking now.

54
00:05:09,535 --> 00:05:11,366
Yeah, I bet it'll
be half-baked.

55
00:05:11,575 --> 00:05:13,008
Well, I'm giving you
my two weeks' notice.

56
00:05:13,255 --> 00:05:14,688
Fay, you can't
do that to me.

57
00:05:14,895 --> 00:05:17,648
Don't tell me you've lost faith in me
after all the hits we've done together.

58
00:05:17,895 --> 00:05:19,533
Yeah, five hits and one error.

59
00:05:19,895 --> 00:05:21,169
Oh, we can fix
the show up.

60
00:05:21,415 --> 00:05:22,689
It's easier to get a new one.

61
00:05:22,935 --> 00:05:25,449
Just a moment. Before you think of leaving
me, you'd better read your contract.

62
00:05:25,655 --> 00:05:28,533
I did, and it made very light reading
in bed last night.

63
00:05:28,775 --> 00:05:33,565
There's a certain little clause about a minimum
weekly gross that lets me out very nicely.

64
00:05:33,815 --> 00:05:36,454
What would you do without me?
Much better.

65
00:05:36,655 --> 00:05:39,123
Wait a minute. There's something
behind all this. What is it?

66
00:05:39,375 --> 00:05:42,572
Simply that I have a tradition
of success to live up to.

67
00:05:42,775 --> 00:05:44,367
Now, Forrest Stanton...

68
00:05:44,615 --> 00:05:46,651
Stanton! Don't tell me
that guy's been after you.

69
00:05:46,895 --> 00:05:48,931
"After" is not the word.

70
00:05:49,135 --> 00:05:53,048
<i>The gentleman approached me
about starring in his Tropicana.</i>

71
00:05:53,295 --> 00:05:55,490
That's fine, that's fine.

72
00:05:55,695 --> 00:05:58,050
You talk to another producer
while I'm still paying you.

73
00:05:58,255 --> 00:05:59,210
[KNOCKING]

74
00:05:59,415 --> 00:06:00,894
<i>Hey, boss.</i>

75
00:06:02,615 --> 00:06:05,493
Come here,
I gotta talk to you.

76
00:06:06,455 --> 00:06:07,570
Hey, boss, we're in trouble.

77
00:06:07,775 --> 00:06:08,924
You trying to be funny?

78
00:06:09,135 --> 00:06:11,410
No, there's a guy upstairs wants to
see you from the Bainbridge Foundation.

79
00:06:11,615 --> 00:06:12,730
Bainbridge Foundation?

80
00:06:12,935 --> 00:06:15,688
Yeah, you know, one of
them clean-up deformers.

81
00:06:15,895 --> 00:06:16,964
Tony:
Send that long-hair in.

82
00:06:17,175 --> 00:06:18,403
Yeah, but this guy
ain't got no hair.

83
00:06:18,615 --> 00:06:20,924
Send him in anyway.
Okay.

84
00:06:22,815 --> 00:06:24,726
Okay, bub.

85
00:06:31,375 --> 00:06:33,491
Good evening, Mr Ferris.
All right, all right.

86
00:06:33,695 --> 00:06:35,526
What's the beef?
Beef?

87
00:06:35,735 --> 00:06:37,726
Well, the last I bought
was 60 cents.

88
00:06:37,935 --> 00:06:38,924
That was hamburger.

89
00:06:39,135 --> 00:06:41,524
Say, I'm in no mood for joking.
What do you want?

90
00:06:41,735 --> 00:06:45,364
Mr Ferris, I have just seen
your show and in my opinion...

91
00:06:45,575 --> 00:06:46,610
That's a lie.

92
00:06:46,815 --> 00:06:49,375
<i>Indiscretions is clean, wholesome
entertainment for the entire family,</i>

93
00:06:49,575 --> 00:06:50,928
and if your organisation
thinks for one moment...

94
00:06:51,135 --> 00:06:53,251
Please, Mr Ferris,
you don't understand.

95
00:06:53,455 --> 00:06:55,093
I liked your show.
What?

96
00:06:55,295 --> 00:06:58,731
Miss Lawrence is the prettiest girl
I've seen since Lillian Russell,

97
00:06:58,935 --> 00:07:00,334
and those indiscrete ladies...

98
00:07:00,575 --> 00:07:03,009
I know all those adjectives.
What do you people want from me?

99
00:07:03,255 --> 00:07:05,371
Well, I'm not representing
the foundation.

100
00:07:05,575 --> 00:07:08,214
I'm only a supply clerk
there, anyway.

101
00:07:08,415 --> 00:07:11,293
I came to ask you to do
something for me, personally.

102
00:07:11,535 --> 00:07:13,685
Oh, now comes the bite.
What do you want?

103
00:07:13,935 --> 00:07:16,847
Well, I have a niece...
I have ulcers.

104
00:07:17,055 --> 00:07:19,649
And compared to my other
troubles, my ulcers are a pleasure.

105
00:07:19,855 --> 00:07:22,244
Well, I'm sorry
about your ulcers,

106
00:07:22,455 --> 00:07:24,844
but my niece, Janey, is
the sweetest, the prettiest,

107
00:07:25,055 --> 00:07:27,888
the most wonderful girl
that you'd ever hope to see.

108
00:07:28,135 --> 00:07:29,614
I hope I never
have to see her.

109
00:07:29,815 --> 00:07:31,487
But she sings
like a meadowlark.

110
00:07:31,695 --> 00:07:32,923
She belongs
in the theatre.

111
00:07:33,135 --> 00:07:35,205
We all have it
in our blood.

112
00:07:35,415 --> 00:07:36,643
Why, years ago,
when I was younger,

113
00:07:36,855 --> 00:07:38,846
I used to sing and
give imitations.

114
00:07:39,055 --> 00:07:40,124
Listen to this.

115
00:07:40,335 --> 00:07:42,087
[SQUAWKS]

116
00:07:42,295 --> 00:07:46,493
[GOBBLING]

117
00:07:46,695 --> 00:07:47,923
That's a turkey.

118
00:07:48,135 --> 00:07:50,012
Are you kidding me?
Oh, no, sir.

119
00:07:50,255 --> 00:07:52,723
Well, I'm not in
the poultry business.

120
00:07:52,935 --> 00:07:54,732
Well, I only do it
for friends.

121
00:07:54,935 --> 00:07:56,334
Well, that's the surest way
to lose them.

122
00:07:56,535 --> 00:07:57,888
What can I do
about all this?

123
00:07:58,095 --> 00:08:00,165
Well, if you'd only
give Janey a chance.

124
00:08:00,375 --> 00:08:02,730
She's always wanted
to appear in a theatre,

125
00:08:02,935 --> 00:08:04,288
and it'd make me
very happy.

126
00:08:04,495 --> 00:08:06,804
Mouse.
Yes, boss.

127
00:08:07,015 --> 00:08:08,334
Show this
imitations man out.

128
00:08:08,535 --> 00:08:10,446
Come on, Mr Foundation.

129
00:08:10,655 --> 00:08:13,010
We've had enough of
your propaganda. Come on.

130
00:08:13,215 --> 00:08:16,764
The way you gentlemen are acting, you'd
think I was having your show raided.

131
00:08:16,975 --> 00:08:20,411
We know all about it.
Say, wait a minute.

132
00:08:20,615 --> 00:08:21,764
Wait a minute.

133
00:08:21,975 --> 00:08:25,206
Mouse, you ought to be ashamed of yourself,
shoving this gentleman around like this.

134
00:08:25,415 --> 00:08:27,167
Take your hands
off him.

135
00:08:27,375 --> 00:08:29,366
Why, you mustn't
rush out like this.

136
00:08:29,575 --> 00:08:31,725
Oh, mustn't I?
Why, no, certainly not.

137
00:08:31,935 --> 00:08:33,209
Sit right down.

138
00:08:33,415 --> 00:08:37,454
Why, I want to tell you, I think
your hen imitation was a natural.

139
00:08:37,655 --> 00:08:38,770
You do?
Yes.

140
00:08:39,015 --> 00:08:42,644
Well, it does come
sort of natural, you know.

141
00:08:42,895 --> 00:08:46,012
Fine. Now about your niece.
I may put her in the show,

142
00:08:46,215 --> 00:08:47,614
that is, if you'll do
something for me too.

143
00:08:47,815 --> 00:08:50,124
You know, you scratch
my back, I scratch yours.

144
00:08:50,375 --> 00:08:52,935
Well, mine doesn't itch, but
I'd be very glad to scratch yours.

145
00:08:53,135 --> 00:08:55,524
No, no, no.

146
00:08:55,735 --> 00:08:58,329
Tell me, how do you
stand with your boss?

147
00:08:58,535 --> 00:09:00,571
Oh, you mean Hannah Bainbridge,
the president?

148
00:09:00,775 --> 00:09:06,054
Yes, how do you rate with her?
I'm her kid brother, Hubert.

149
00:09:06,255 --> 00:09:09,804
Hubert, how would you like
to get out of the supply room?

150
00:09:10,015 --> 00:09:11,971
Well, it is a little
close in there.

151
00:09:12,175 --> 00:09:15,167
I understand.
Just a second.

152
00:09:15,375 --> 00:09:17,730
Just a second, Hubert.

153
00:09:19,095 --> 00:09:20,130
Take a look.

154
00:09:21,295 --> 00:09:22,330
What do you see?

155
00:09:22,535 --> 00:09:25,368
Oh, that's more than
I've seen in years.

156
00:09:25,575 --> 00:09:27,645
Put it in your pocket.

157
00:09:27,855 --> 00:09:29,573
That's enough.

158
00:09:29,775 --> 00:09:34,405
I have an idea that will land you
on the very top of your foundation.

159
00:09:34,615 --> 00:09:36,367
You have?
Yes.

160
00:09:36,575 --> 00:09:39,647
What's the idea?
Well, I'll tell you.

161
00:09:55,615 --> 00:09:57,845
[BELL RINGS]

162
00:09:58,055 --> 00:09:59,534
Hello, Janey.
Good morning, Uncle Hubert.

163
00:09:59,735 --> 00:10:01,885
What happened to you?
I was worried.

164
00:10:02,095 --> 00:10:03,653
Aunt Hannah's been
calling for you.

165
00:10:03,855 --> 00:10:06,847
She has?
Oh, dear, dear.

166
00:10:07,055 --> 00:10:09,250
Well, I'd better go right in.

167
00:10:09,455 --> 00:10:13,573
Oh, Uncle, did you see that man?
You know, the one you told me about?

168
00:10:13,775 --> 00:10:16,733
Did I see him? I not only
saw him, I talked to him.

169
00:10:16,935 --> 00:10:19,324
No!
You're as good as set.

170
00:10:19,535 --> 00:10:21,287
All I have to do
is see Hannah.

171
00:10:21,495 --> 00:10:23,213
Aunt Hannah?
You'll find out.

172
00:10:23,415 --> 00:10:25,212
Now, just keep
your fingers crossed.

173
00:10:25,415 --> 00:10:26,848
On both hands.

174
00:10:27,055 --> 00:10:28,773
<i>HANNAH:
Hubert!</i>

175
00:10:36,495 --> 00:10:39,134
HANNAH:
Yes, one round trip to Seattle.

176
00:10:39,335 --> 00:10:45,046
Essential? What is more essential than the
moral welfare of our young people in these times?

177
00:10:45,255 --> 00:10:49,294
I tell you, my presence at our
convention is absolutely imperative.

178
00:10:49,495 --> 00:10:52,089
Are you going somewhere,
Hannah? Shut up.

179
00:10:52,295 --> 00:10:58,768
You say I can get an upper? I suppose
it's the best I can do. Thank you.

180
00:10:59,015 --> 00:11:01,324
Now, Mr Playboy,
where were you last night?

181
00:11:01,575 --> 00:11:03,725
I went to a show.
A show?

182
00:11:03,935 --> 00:11:06,449
<i>Indiscretions of 1943.</i>

183
00:11:06,655 --> 00:11:09,965
Hubert Bainbridge.
But it was an accident, Hannah.

184
00:11:10,175 --> 00:11:15,124
I was on my way to the Y for a workout,
and I happened to pass the theatre.

185
00:11:15,335 --> 00:11:19,772
When I saw the pictures on the
outside, I couldn't resist going in.

186
00:11:19,975 --> 00:11:22,091
But only in the interests
of the foundation.

187
00:11:22,335 --> 00:11:24,803
Isn't your interest in
our work rather sudden?

188
00:11:25,055 --> 00:11:28,843
Well, I admit my heart
hasn't always been in it.

189
00:11:29,055 --> 00:11:32,684
But last night was more
than I could stand.

190
00:11:32,895 --> 00:11:36,524
Look. Did you ever see
anything so brazen?

191
00:11:36,775 --> 00:11:39,573
Did you?
Positively shocking.

192
00:11:39,775 --> 00:11:42,050
Send them a stern warning.
Form 92.

193
00:11:42,255 --> 00:11:45,930
Form 92? This is something
that calls for action.

194
00:11:47,055 --> 00:11:49,330
You should see what
she does with her hips.

195
00:11:49,535 --> 00:11:53,130
Why, it's practically
the hootchy-kootchy.

196
00:11:53,335 --> 00:11:54,563
[HUMMING "LITTLE EGYPT"]

197
00:11:54,775 --> 00:11:57,369
Hubert! I'm sorry, Hannah,
but that's what she does.

198
00:11:57,615 --> 00:11:59,890
I'll take care of her as soon as
I get back from the convention.

199
00:12:00,135 --> 00:12:01,773
But that may be too late.

200
00:12:01,975 --> 00:12:05,092
Think of the thousands of people
that may see this exhibition.

201
00:12:05,295 --> 00:12:08,332
I tell you, Hannah, this show
should be closed tonight.

202
00:12:14,415 --> 00:12:19,011
COP:
Bring down that curtain.

203
00:12:22,015 --> 00:12:23,892
Ladies and gentlemen,
this show is closed.

204
00:12:24,095 --> 00:12:26,529
If you'll go to the box office,
there will be an officer who will see

205
00:12:26,735 --> 00:12:29,932
that your admission is
cheerfully refunded. Thank you.

206
00:12:38,975 --> 00:12:43,844
What a break. Why, you couldn't
buy publicity like that.

207
00:12:48,055 --> 00:12:49,693
Look, doesn't that
make up for last night?

208
00:12:49,935 --> 00:12:51,846
I wouldn't be surprised if
you framed this yourself.

209
00:12:52,055 --> 00:12:53,932
Well, what would you say
if I told you that I did?

210
00:12:54,135 --> 00:12:57,366
Well, it's all right.
Tell her, Mouse.

211
00:12:57,575 --> 00:12:59,486
He figured it all out himself,
Miss Lawrence.

212
00:12:59,695 --> 00:13:01,765
He's got terrific connections.

213
00:13:02,535 --> 00:13:04,765
CAPTAIN: All right,
folks, clear the lobby.

214
00:13:04,975 --> 00:13:06,567
The show is closed indefinitely.

215
00:13:06,775 --> 00:13:08,606
[PEOPLE GRUMBLING]

216
00:13:08,815 --> 00:13:10,328
Tell them to close
that box office.

217
00:13:10,535 --> 00:13:11,968
FERRIS: Hey, what's
going on around here?

218
00:13:12,215 --> 00:13:14,046
Hello, Mr Ferris.
Your show is closed.

219
00:13:14,255 --> 00:13:15,688
But this must be a mistake.

220
00:13:15,895 --> 00:13:18,853
You're right, Mr Ferris, and whoever
stirred up that Bainbridge outfit

221
00:13:19,055 --> 00:13:20,090
is the guy who made it.

222
00:13:20,335 --> 00:13:21,814
It was just a gag.

223
00:13:22,015 --> 00:13:23,812
Well, if it was before,
it ain't now.

224
00:13:24,015 --> 00:13:25,050
The heat's on.

225
00:13:25,255 --> 00:13:26,768
We're closing up
two more shows tonight.

226
00:13:27,015 --> 00:13:28,494
Anything wrong, captain?

227
00:13:28,735 --> 00:13:31,454
Yes, Miss Lawrence.
We've gotta close it up.

228
00:13:31,655 --> 00:13:33,771
That's one job I sure hate:
closing shows.

229
00:13:34,015 --> 00:13:36,688
Well, Mastermind, did you
trip over your connection?

230
00:13:36,935 --> 00:13:39,324
I'll fix this just as soon
as I can get to a phone.

231
00:13:39,535 --> 00:13:41,491
The Mayor himself couldn't
fix this one, Mr Ferris.

232
00:13:41,735 --> 00:13:44,090
When bigger and better fixes
are made, you'll get into them,

233
00:13:44,295 --> 00:13:46,729
but from now on, without me.

234
00:13:49,815 --> 00:13:53,330
Pardon me for saying it, Mr Ferris, but that's the
best thing that could have happened to that show.

235
00:13:53,535 --> 00:13:54,888
Oh, no, I'm a ruined man.

236
00:13:55,095 --> 00:13:57,563
On the contrary, that show would have
ruined both you and Miss Lawrence.

237
00:13:57,775 --> 00:13:59,003
It was a dud.

238
00:13:59,215 --> 00:14:01,490
Now you can take a little rest
and then put on something good.

239
00:14:01,695 --> 00:14:03,686
Rest. How can I
take a rest?

240
00:14:03,895 --> 00:14:06,728
Why not, Mr Ferris? Go to Florida
and get some of that sunshine.

241
00:14:06,935 --> 00:14:08,607
What's going to happen to
Fay Lawrence in the meantime?

242
00:14:08,815 --> 00:14:10,043
Fay Lawrence?
Yes.

243
00:14:10,255 --> 00:14:12,325
Do you think she'd wait around
until I got a coat of tan?

244
00:14:12,535 --> 00:14:13,888
Mr Ferris, you mean
you didn't hear?

245
00:14:14,095 --> 00:14:16,893
Hear what?
Come here, just a minute.

246
00:14:18,855 --> 00:14:20,254
Take a look.

247
00:14:24,855 --> 00:14:26,368
That can't be possible.

248
00:14:26,575 --> 00:14:28,486
Well, we got notice
to vacate the theatre.

249
00:14:28,695 --> 00:14:30,731
Fay can't do this to me.

250
00:14:30,935 --> 00:14:34,564
She told me something about Stanton,
but I thought it was only to get my goat.

251
00:14:34,775 --> 00:14:36,208
Why, this is awful.

252
00:14:37,895 --> 00:14:39,647
We're sorry we're late,
Mr Ferris.

253
00:14:39,855 --> 00:14:41,208
So it's you.

254
00:14:41,415 --> 00:14:44,054
Yeah, this is me, and
this is my niece, Janey.

255
00:14:44,255 --> 00:14:46,610
How do you do?
You're just the guy I wanted to see.

256
00:14:46,815 --> 00:14:50,444
Yeah, was that raid very funny?
Funny. I'm still in stitches.

257
00:14:50,655 --> 00:14:52,213
Well, I'm glad you liked it.

258
00:14:52,415 --> 00:14:56,294
And you were right, Mr Ferris, I'm
in complete charge of the foundation

259
00:14:56,495 --> 00:15:00,170
because my sister, Hannah, has gone to
Seattle and will be there for two months.

260
00:15:00,375 --> 00:15:01,649
I'm overwhelmed.

261
00:15:01,855 --> 00:15:04,449
Yeah, I feel pretty good
about it myself.

262
00:15:04,655 --> 00:15:07,249
But I suppose you're anxious
to hear Janey sing.

263
00:15:07,455 --> 00:15:09,332
You get your music out, darling.

264
00:15:09,535 --> 00:15:11,446
I always play for her.

265
00:15:14,535 --> 00:15:18,084
Mr Ferris, aren't you going
to wait to hear Janey sing?

266
00:15:22,855 --> 00:15:25,005
Gee, Janey, I'm sorry.

267
00:15:25,215 --> 00:15:26,694
Something must have come up.

268
00:15:26,895 --> 00:15:29,125
He was so anxious
to hear you yesterday.

269
00:15:29,335 --> 00:15:30,768
Yesterday he still
had a show.

270
00:15:31,015 --> 00:15:34,212
Oh, it's all right, Uncle Hubert.
You did your best.

271
00:15:34,415 --> 00:15:36,167
Let's go home.

272
00:15:38,775 --> 00:15:41,414
I'm awful sorry, honey.

273
00:15:47,855 --> 00:15:54,408
[SINGING XAVIER CUGAT'S
"NEGRA LEONO"]

274
00:16:15,215 --> 00:16:16,614
WOMAN:
Good evening, Mr Ferris.

275
00:16:16,815 --> 00:16:17,804
<i>Bonsoir, monsieur Ferris.</i>

276
00:16:18,015 --> 00:16:19,607
Hello, mac.

277
00:17:57,255 --> 00:17:59,849
<i>Tony.
Xavier. Mi amigo mejor.</i>

278
00:18:00,055 --> 00:18:03,809
Tony, my friend. I can always
depend on you to fill one booth, huh?

279
00:18:04,015 --> 00:18:05,812
Wonderful music.
Wonderful.

280
00:18:06,015 --> 00:18:09,007
You know, I should have my head examined
for never using you in one of my shows.

281
00:18:09,215 --> 00:18:11,683
But the next one I do,
you'll be in it.

282
00:18:12,255 --> 00:18:14,644
Oh, I'm afraid I'll be tied up
for quite some time, Tony.

283
00:18:14,855 --> 00:18:16,573
<i>I've just signed with
Stanton for Tropicana.</i>

284
00:18:16,775 --> 00:18:18,606
Don't tell me you're gonna
work for Stanton too?

285
00:18:18,815 --> 00:18:21,124
Why not? He gave me a good
contract and it's a great show.

286
00:18:21,335 --> 00:18:23,087
Great show. Wait till you see
the one I'm working on.

287
00:18:23,295 --> 00:18:25,445
A real dynamite musical
if you've ever seen one.

288
00:18:25,655 --> 00:18:28,328
What is it about?
Well, it's a terrific idea.

289
00:18:28,535 --> 00:18:32,574
It's one of those sensational
things, I... Tell him, Mouse.

290
00:18:32,775 --> 00:18:35,130
Huh? Well, you told me
not to tell anybody.

291
00:18:35,335 --> 00:18:38,168
That's all right. You can
tell him, he's my friend.

292
00:18:38,375 --> 00:18:42,414
Well, uh,
it's about India.

293
00:18:42,615 --> 00:18:47,086
Maharajas, beautiful girls,
a magic carpet.

294
00:18:47,335 --> 00:18:48,609
It sounds vague.

295
00:18:48,855 --> 00:18:51,050
Well, I'm working
on the script now.

296
00:18:51,255 --> 00:18:52,483
Tony, you're
shadow-boxing again.

297
00:18:52,695 --> 00:18:54,731
You can't even tell a good lie
for a friend anymore.

298
00:18:54,935 --> 00:18:57,403
<i>Tell me, is Tropicana
really that good?</i>

299
00:18:57,615 --> 00:18:59,526
Oh, great, great.

300
00:18:59,735 --> 00:19:02,727
How is Fay in it?
It's gonna hurt, Tony.

301
00:19:02,935 --> 00:19:04,812
Oh, I can stand it.
I don't really care anymore.

302
00:19:05,055 --> 00:19:08,604
What Stanton's trying to do is bring a
new Fay Lawrence out of the old shell,

303
00:19:08,815 --> 00:19:10,089
to create a new personality.

304
00:19:10,335 --> 00:19:12,485
It can't be done.
He's doing it.

305
00:19:12,735 --> 00:19:14,373
You ought to see
some of those rehearsals.

306
00:19:16,295 --> 00:19:17,648
Don't go to pieces, Tony.

307
00:19:17,855 --> 00:19:19,732
Broadway is full of eager
and talented people.

308
00:19:19,935 --> 00:19:21,448
You created one Fay Lawrence,
you'll create another.

309
00:19:21,655 --> 00:19:22,644
Oh, sure.

310
00:19:22,895 --> 00:19:25,728
Oh, I'd better go back
to my band, Tony.

311
00:19:25,935 --> 00:19:28,369
I must hold onto the boys
I still have.

312
00:19:28,575 --> 00:19:32,534
You know, most of them are already tooting
reveille in Green River, North Carolina.

313
00:19:32,735 --> 00:19:34,327
Goodbye, Tony.

314
00:19:34,575 --> 00:19:37,487
Stanton, that cheap,
double-crossing crook.

315
00:19:37,695 --> 00:19:39,208
Bringing out a new
Fay Lawrence.

316
00:19:39,415 --> 00:19:40,609
What does he know
about her anyway?

317
00:19:40,815 --> 00:19:42,885
Mouse, have I ever
lied to you?

318
00:19:43,095 --> 00:19:45,086
Well, not unless
you had to, no.

319
00:19:45,295 --> 00:19:46,284
Then listen to me.

320
00:19:46,495 --> 00:19:48,167
Fay Lawrence is part of me.
She's me.

321
00:19:48,375 --> 00:19:51,367
Do you think I'm gonna let anybody
twist her around and ruin my life's work?

322
00:19:51,575 --> 00:19:52,928
Sounds like
he's doing it, boss.

323
00:19:53,135 --> 00:19:56,047
I don't believe it. I've gotta
see that with my own eyes.

324
00:19:56,255 --> 00:19:57,768
And I'm going to tomorrow.

325
00:20:04,655 --> 00:20:05,929
Well, boss, it was no lie.

326
00:20:06,135 --> 00:20:07,170
They haven't opened yet.

327
00:20:07,375 --> 00:20:08,364
Yeah, they gotta
rehearse first.

328
00:20:08,575 --> 00:20:11,214
Come on, let's go in
and take a peak.

329
00:21:01,775 --> 00:21:05,165
<i>There goes that guitar</i>

330
00:21:05,375 --> 00:21:08,924
<i>I knew it would start again</i>

331
00:21:09,135 --> 00:21:15,688
<i>And there goes my heart again
Singing along</i>

332
00:21:15,895 --> 00:21:19,808
<i>There goes that guitar</i>

333
00:21:20,015 --> 00:21:22,973
<i>And there goes that chord again</i>

334
00:21:23,215 --> 00:21:27,254
<i>And I'm overboard again</i>

335
00:21:27,455 --> 00:21:30,492
<i>Is it that song?</i>

336
00:21:30,695 --> 00:21:34,529
<i>Or is it love?</i>

337
00:21:34,735 --> 00:21:38,091
<i>I know that you're near to me</i>

338
00:21:38,295 --> 00:21:41,924
<i>And that makes it clear to me</i>

339
00:21:42,135 --> 00:21:48,404
<i>This is the start of love</i>

340
00:21:48,615 --> 00:21:52,005
<i>And it's gone too far</i>

341
00:21:52,215 --> 00:21:55,924
<i>There goes that guitar</i>

342
00:21:56,175 --> 00:22:00,726
<i>There goes my heart</i>

343
00:23:53,815 --> 00:23:58,730
<i>Or is it love?</i>

344
00:23:58,935 --> 00:24:02,814
<i>I know that you're near to me</i>

345
00:24:03,015 --> 00:24:06,371
<i>And that makes it clear to me</i>

346
00:24:06,575 --> 00:24:12,889
<i>This is the start of love</i>

347
00:24:13,095 --> 00:24:16,451
<i>And it's gone too far</i>

348
00:24:16,655 --> 00:24:20,204
<i>There goes that guitar</i>

349
00:24:20,415 --> 00:24:24,044
<i>There goes my heart</i>

350
00:24:24,255 --> 00:24:29,727
<i>There goes my heart</i>

351
00:24:29,975 --> 00:24:31,772
How do you like
the number, Fay?

352
00:24:31,975 --> 00:24:33,886
I don't want to okay anything
unless you're enthusiastic about it.

353
00:24:34,135 --> 00:24:36,171
Oh, I always say yes
to a good number.

354
00:24:36,415 --> 00:24:39,851
You know, Fay, I'm convinced that this show is going
to give you the greatest scope for your talents.

355
00:24:40,055 --> 00:24:41,488
I told you I'd surround you
with the best.

356
00:24:41,735 --> 00:24:45,808
Anyway, I'm so glad to be with someone
who can keep his word... I hope.

357
00:24:47,015 --> 00:24:49,165
That's appreciation for you.

358
00:24:49,775 --> 00:24:51,333
Pardon me, Miss Lawrence,
your number's on next.

359
00:24:51,575 --> 00:24:54,408
Uh, did you decide to drive in on
the gaucho carriage for this number?

360
00:24:54,615 --> 00:24:57,573
No, dear, I'm coming in
on my own momentum.

361
00:24:58,695 --> 00:25:00,845
I can't let her
get away with this.

362
00:25:01,055 --> 00:25:03,125
I've gotta talk to her.

363
00:25:06,055 --> 00:25:07,374
FAY: Be sure you don't
wear that tonight.

364
00:25:07,575 --> 00:25:11,568
Oh, no, madame.

365
00:25:11,775 --> 00:25:13,652
Get out.
But monsieur Ferris...

366
00:25:13,855 --> 00:25:16,050
Get out and stay out.

367
00:25:19,575 --> 00:25:21,213
The late Mr Ferris, I presume.

368
00:25:21,415 --> 00:25:23,804
Fay, I heard every word you said
to that cheap four-flusher Stanton.

369
00:25:24,055 --> 00:25:25,647
I was sitting in the balcony,
right over your head.

370
00:25:25,855 --> 00:25:27,732
As an aerial umbrella,
you're a perfect drip.

371
00:25:27,935 --> 00:25:29,448
You've gotta listen, Fay,
this doesn't make sense.

372
00:25:29,655 --> 00:25:31,725
You can't work for Stanton after
all the shows we've done together.

373
00:25:31,935 --> 00:25:34,051
Think of my reputation.
Don't be tiresome.

374
00:25:34,255 --> 00:25:35,734
What do you want
to do, ruin me?

375
00:25:35,935 --> 00:25:37,891
Put me in bankruptcy?
Send me to jail?

376
00:25:38,095 --> 00:25:40,609
You know I've been mad about you
from the first time I laid eyes on you.

377
00:25:40,815 --> 00:25:43,170
You're my whole world. What do you
want to do, drive me to a madhouse?

378
00:25:43,455 --> 00:25:44,854
No, I'll call you a taxi.

379
00:25:45,055 --> 00:25:47,410
Listen, honey, you can't cast me
aside like an old shoe.

380
00:25:47,615 --> 00:25:49,651
Don't be silly. Who's throwing
away old shoes nowadays?

381
00:25:49,895 --> 00:25:52,534
Fay, if you come back to me,
we'll get right back on top again.

382
00:25:52,735 --> 00:25:53,963
I've got some great plans.

383
00:25:54,175 --> 00:25:56,973
Why, only this morning, I got you the
greatest proposition you've ever seen.

384
00:25:57,175 --> 00:25:59,484
What is it? Why, we'll sweep
right over Broadway again.

385
00:25:59,695 --> 00:26:01,606
We'll have lines ten blocks long
in front of our box office.

386
00:26:01,815 --> 00:26:03,168
We'll have them hanging
from the rafters.

387
00:26:03,375 --> 00:26:04,933
And another thing: if you give
Stanton your notice today,

388
00:26:05,135 --> 00:26:06,363
I'll double your salary
in my next show.

389
00:26:06,575 --> 00:26:07,530
What do you think of that?

390
00:26:07,775 --> 00:26:09,333
Oh, don't be mercenary.

391
00:26:09,535 --> 00:26:11,844
Money isn't everything,
if you can get it.

392
00:26:12,095 --> 00:26:14,325
Doesn't your conscience
ever bother you?

393
00:26:14,575 --> 00:26:15,974
No, it amuses me.

394
00:26:16,215 --> 00:26:18,968
Have you ever thanked me once
for everything I've done for you?

395
00:26:19,215 --> 00:26:21,570
I only answer $64 questions.

396
00:26:21,775 --> 00:26:24,528
All right, Fay, you asked for it.

397
00:26:26,295 --> 00:26:30,652
When I start fighting, I get mad,
and when I get mad, I bite nails in two.

398
00:26:30,855 --> 00:26:32,493
All right, I'll get you
a priority on them.

399
00:26:32,695 --> 00:26:33,844
[GROANS]

400
00:26:38,415 --> 00:26:39,928
Private Andy Walker
reporting for duty.

401
00:26:40,135 --> 00:26:42,365
At ease, soldier.

402
00:26:42,575 --> 00:26:44,930
Boy, am I glad to see you.

403
00:26:48,575 --> 00:26:50,964
Well, what can I investigate
for you today?

404
00:26:51,175 --> 00:26:53,006
Any burlesque show
I ought to peep at?

405
00:26:53,215 --> 00:26:54,967
No, darling,
no investigations.

406
00:26:55,175 --> 00:26:57,769
Things are so quiet around here,
I might just as well be in the morgue.

407
00:26:57,975 --> 00:26:59,203
Well, don't let it
get you down, honey.

408
00:26:59,415 --> 00:27:01,451
As soon as I get this war
over with, I'll marry you.

409
00:27:01,655 --> 00:27:02,644
I'll get you out of here.

410
00:27:02,855 --> 00:27:07,007
But in the meantime, I'd like to be able to prove to
myself just what my chances are for a stage career.

411
00:27:07,215 --> 00:27:09,729
Oh, Janey, dear, I still say you'll
never be happy in show business.

412
00:27:09,935 --> 00:27:11,573
I don't want to see you
get hurt by it.

413
00:27:11,775 --> 00:27:13,493
Why do you feel you have
to be a famous star?

414
00:27:13,695 --> 00:27:15,970
Oh, Andy, it's not
the fame I'm after.

415
00:27:16,175 --> 00:27:17,574
It's a chance to prove
what I can do.

416
00:27:17,775 --> 00:27:19,174
But it's such
a nerve-racking life.

417
00:27:19,375 --> 00:27:22,014
But don't you think it's nerve-racking
sitting around here day after day?

418
00:27:22,215 --> 00:27:24,490
I can almost feel the spiders
spinning their webs around me.

419
00:27:24,735 --> 00:27:27,807
Good morning. Hello, Janey.

420
00:27:28,015 --> 00:27:30,768
Why, where's my friend, Hubert?
Oh, it's you, Mr Ferris.

421
00:27:30,975 --> 00:27:32,886
So you're the big producer
she was telling me about, huh?

422
00:27:33,095 --> 00:27:35,928
Well, I know you think I walked out on
you, but that's what I came up to explain.

423
00:27:36,175 --> 00:27:38,530
Always glad to meet
one of our boys.

424
00:27:38,775 --> 00:27:40,288
I'm gonna make a big star
out of you.

425
00:27:40,535 --> 00:27:41,968
Yeah, and he's the one can do it.

426
00:27:42,175 --> 00:27:44,006
He's produced more hits
than any man on Broadway.

427
00:27:44,255 --> 00:27:46,689
Yeah? If he doesn't get out of here,
I'll produce one right on his chin.

428
00:27:46,895 --> 00:27:47,884
Oh, Andy, please,
you'll ruin everything.

429
00:27:48,095 --> 00:27:49,653
Are you on the level,
or are you just bluffing?

430
00:27:49,855 --> 00:27:51,254
Bluffing? I'll show you
whether I'm bluffing or not.

431
00:27:51,455 --> 00:27:53,525
Wait till you hear the great news
I've got for your Uncle Hubert.

432
00:27:53,775 --> 00:27:55,686
Hey, what's going on here?

433
00:27:55,935 --> 00:27:59,689
Hubert, Hubert, we're gonna produce
the biggest show that ever hit Broadway,

434
00:27:59,895 --> 00:28:01,692
and Janey's gonna
play the lead.

435
00:28:01,895 --> 00:28:03,965
Honest?
I give you my solemn word of honour.

436
00:28:04,215 --> 00:28:05,284
I don't believe you've got one.

437
00:28:05,535 --> 00:28:06,684
What have I ever done to you?

438
00:28:06,935 --> 00:28:09,369
Andy doesn't want me to go
on the stage, Mr Ferris.

439
00:28:09,615 --> 00:28:12,209
What? And cheat the public
of her charm and personality?

440
00:28:12,415 --> 00:28:13,689
You're not gonna stand
for that, are you?

441
00:28:13,895 --> 00:28:15,089
No, I should say not.

442
00:28:15,295 --> 00:28:17,013
Let's get down to business.
Come right in the office here.

443
00:28:17,215 --> 00:28:18,170
That's it.

444
00:28:18,375 --> 00:28:21,014
[SPEAKING IN SPANISH]
Yes.

445
00:28:21,215 --> 00:28:23,251
Come on, Hubert, sit down,
make yourself comfortable.

446
00:28:23,455 --> 00:28:24,410
Well, thank you.

447
00:28:24,615 --> 00:28:26,207
You still want Janey to get
a break, don't you?

448
00:28:26,415 --> 00:28:27,404
Of course I do.

449
00:28:27,615 --> 00:28:31,005
Well, then we've got to team her up
with some big New York name.

450
00:28:31,215 --> 00:28:33,285
Oh, like...
Well, not exactly.

451
00:28:33,495 --> 00:28:36,407
Some great personality like,
uh, Fay Lawrence.

452
00:28:36,615 --> 00:28:38,685
Oh, she's wonderful.
Yes, but here's the trouble.

453
00:28:38,895 --> 00:28:41,090
She's already signed
with Forrest Stanton.

454
00:28:41,295 --> 00:28:42,694
Gee, that's too bad.
Yes.

455
00:28:42,895 --> 00:28:44,931
Someone must get her
away from him.

456
00:28:45,135 --> 00:28:46,329
And you're the man
to do it.

457
00:28:46,575 --> 00:28:50,887
Well, I'm a little out of practice,
but I'll be glad to try.

458
00:28:51,095 --> 00:28:54,053
All you have to do is take the phone.
Call Stanton. Tell him who you are.

459
00:28:54,255 --> 00:28:57,327
Then sort of drop a hint that he'd
better not use Fay Lawrence in his show.

460
00:28:57,535 --> 00:28:58,490
Well, I don't understand.

461
00:28:58,695 --> 00:29:00,333
You don't have to understand.

462
00:29:00,535 --> 00:29:03,607
She's still on the foundation's
blacklist, isn't she?

463
00:29:03,815 --> 00:29:05,487
We have no blacklist.

464
00:29:05,735 --> 00:29:08,329
You have one now.

465
00:29:12,535 --> 00:29:14,253
[INTERCOM BUZZES]

466
00:29:14,455 --> 00:29:15,410
Yes?

467
00:29:15,615 --> 00:29:17,173
MAN [OVER INTERCOM]: The Bainbridge
Foundation on the phone, sir.

468
00:29:17,375 --> 00:29:21,163
<i>Bainbridge Foundation?
It's Mr Bainbridge himself.</i>

469
00:29:21,375 --> 00:29:22,603
Hello.

470
00:29:22,815 --> 00:29:24,373
Yes.

471
00:29:24,575 --> 00:29:26,725
Oh, how do you do,
Mr Bainbridge?

472
00:29:26,935 --> 00:29:28,493
Of course she's going
to be in my show. Why?

473
00:29:28,735 --> 00:29:32,648
Well, she's still on
our blacklist, Mr Stanton.

474
00:29:32,855 --> 00:29:36,848
Of course, this is unofficial, but I
thought I'd warn you in a friendly way.

475
00:29:37,095 --> 00:29:41,293
Oh, but Mr Bainbridge, don't you think
that your organization is being very unfair?

476
00:29:41,495 --> 00:29:43,406
I mean, after all, Miss Lawrence
is a big Broadway star.

477
00:29:43,615 --> 00:29:46,607
I've built my entire show around her.

478
00:29:46,815 --> 00:29:47,850
But that's a restraint of trade.

479
00:29:48,095 --> 00:29:52,486
Restraint of trade?
It's just a friendly tip.

480
00:29:52,695 --> 00:29:55,846
Of course, this is just a friendly tip.

481
00:29:56,055 --> 00:30:00,651
And I happen to know
what they're figuring on doing.

482
00:30:00,855 --> 00:30:02,652
Yes, that's right.

483
00:30:02,855 --> 00:30:04,891
Oh, not at all, Mr Stanton.

484
00:30:05,095 --> 00:30:06,926
Goodbye.

485
00:30:07,135 --> 00:30:09,126
What'd he say?
He thanked me.

486
00:30:09,335 --> 00:30:10,484
Wonderful.

487
00:30:10,695 --> 00:30:13,255
Now we give him
our slow curve.

488
00:30:23,855 --> 00:30:26,210
<i>Listen, I've got a story to tell you</i>

489
00:30:26,415 --> 00:30:28,849
<i>About a yank who came
South of the border</i>

490
00:30:29,055 --> 00:30:32,684
<i>He makes me so happy
And so mad</i>

491
00:30:32,895 --> 00:30:34,453
<i>But, oh, he's such a Romeo</i>

492
00:30:39,655 --> 00:30:44,524
[ALL SINGING
RHYTHMIC SOUNDS]

493
00:30:49,095 --> 00:30:54,772
<i>Antonio, Antonio
He is such a Romeo</i>

494
00:30:58,695 --> 00:31:04,452
<i>Antonio, Antonio
He is so magnífico</i>

495
00:31:08,255 --> 00:31:12,771
<i>He tries American tactics
Makes eyes wherever he be</i>

496
00:31:12,975 --> 00:31:18,208
<i>Now I'm so mad I could kill him
Why doesn't he make eyes at me?</i>

497
00:31:22,335 --> 00:31:28,251
<i>But Antonio, Antonio
He is so romántico</i>

498
00:31:31,975 --> 00:31:34,728
<i>He plays the piano
He's such a man-o</i>

499
00:31:34,935 --> 00:31:37,210
<i>So magnífico</i>

500
00:31:45,855 --> 00:31:49,643
<i>He plays the piccolo
Oh, how I love him so</i>

501
00:32:00,095 --> 00:32:02,689
<i>He shakes maraca
Chic-chic-chic chaca</i>

502
00:32:02,895 --> 00:32:05,329
<i>Ah, bravissimo!</i>

503
00:32:14,855 --> 00:32:19,485
<i>BAND: Antonio, Antonio
He's such a Romeo</i></i>

504
00:32:19,695 --> 00:32:21,651
<i>Romántico Antonio
He give me such baloney, oh!</i>

505
00:32:21,855 --> 00:32:23,811
<i>He's such a braggadocio
About the things he does</i>

506
00:32:24,015 --> 00:32:28,486
<i>BAND: Antonio, Antonio
He is so magnífico</i></i>

507
00:32:28,695 --> 00:32:31,129
<i>Now here I am so all alone
Without a single chaperone</i>

508
00:32:31,335 --> 00:32:33,007
<i>And he is flirting
With somebody else</i>

509
00:32:33,255 --> 00:32:37,806
<i>He serenades señoritas
Each night wherever he be</i>

510
00:32:38,015 --> 00:32:39,687
<i>He plays guitar with such passion</i>

511
00:32:45,175 --> 00:32:48,087
<i>Why doesn't he play it for me?</i>

512
00:32:52,095 --> 00:32:56,452
<i>But Antonio, Antonio
If we should ever marry, oh</i>

513
00:32:56,655 --> 00:33:01,490
<i>We'd have Eduardo,
Manuelito, Roberto, Pepito</i>

514
00:33:01,695 --> 00:33:04,493
<i>Pablito, Panchito</i>

515
00:33:04,695 --> 00:33:07,892
<i>Oh, we'd have so many chiquitos</i>

516
00:33:14,455 --> 00:33:16,491
<i>Bonsoir, monsieur Ferris.
Is Lou here?</i>

517
00:33:16,695 --> 00:33:18,811
Yeah, dancing with the dumbest
girl this side of the Rocky Mountains.

518
00:33:19,015 --> 00:33:20,573
I saved the booth for you
next to Mr Stanton's.

519
00:33:20,775 --> 00:33:22,333
He looks real worried tonight.

520
00:33:22,535 --> 00:33:23,809
You're a real pal, mac.

521
00:33:24,055 --> 00:33:25,454
I'm gonna make you stage
manager in the new show.

522
00:33:25,655 --> 00:33:27,850
Thank you, Mr Ferris. I can do
the black-face too, you know.

523
00:33:28,495 --> 00:33:30,087
Mac, tell Louis Shore
I wanna see him.

524
00:33:30,295 --> 00:33:31,250
I think Mr Shore is dancing.

525
00:33:31,455 --> 00:33:33,366
Tell him it's important, if he
wants to make some quick dough.

526
00:33:33,575 --> 00:33:34,894
Yes, Mr Ferris.

527
00:33:49,215 --> 00:33:50,773
Sorry, honey, business.

528
00:33:50,975 --> 00:33:53,443
Go powder your nose
or something.

529
00:33:53,655 --> 00:33:55,964
Hello, Ferris, what's the story?
Well, I'm in a tough spot.

530
00:33:56,175 --> 00:33:57,164
You're telling me.

531
00:33:57,415 --> 00:34:00,134
I've got $200,000 lined up
to do a musical,

532
00:34:00,335 --> 00:34:02,644
so I want some real
sensational people.

533
00:34:02,855 --> 00:34:04,447
Well, I've got them all,
you know.

534
00:34:04,655 --> 00:34:06,691
What type of a show is it?
Well, I'm angling around.

535
00:34:06,895 --> 00:34:08,647
I've read a couple of scripts.

536
00:34:08,855 --> 00:34:09,844
Who've you got?

537
00:34:10,055 --> 00:34:12,615
Well, I've got Lucille Wright,
Chiquita Benton, Stafford and Lynn,

538
00:34:12,815 --> 00:34:14,931
Bill Weston and his
Seven Swing-Slingers.

539
00:34:15,135 --> 00:34:16,329
No, that's no good.

540
00:34:16,535 --> 00:34:18,093
No good?
What do you mean, "no good"?

541
00:34:18,295 --> 00:34:20,172
Who do you want? Shostakovich
and his seven symphonies?

542
00:34:20,375 --> 00:34:23,606
No, I've got to have the best there
is on Broadway, and no fooling.

543
00:34:26,135 --> 00:34:27,887
I gotta rush now.
Big deal is cooking.

544
00:34:28,095 --> 00:34:29,210
I'll give you a call
Monday, Tony.

545
00:34:29,415 --> 00:34:30,814
I'll see what I can
line up for you.

546
00:34:31,015 --> 00:34:33,575
Give my best to Malnick.
I will.

547
00:34:37,895 --> 00:34:38,930
Hello, Tony.

548
00:34:39,135 --> 00:34:40,693
Forrest.
Mind if I sit down?

549
00:34:40,895 --> 00:34:41,805
Why, of course not.

550
00:34:42,015 --> 00:34:45,087
Say, what are you doing here? I thought
you were all tied up with your rehearsals.

551
00:34:45,295 --> 00:34:47,729
Say, how does the show look?
Tony, it's a gold-mine.

552
00:34:47,935 --> 00:34:48,890
So they tell me.

553
00:34:49,135 --> 00:34:52,810
Oh, by the way, I couldn't help but overhear your
conversation with Lou just now. Congratulations.

554
00:34:53,055 --> 00:34:54,568
Thanks. I did hit the jackpot.

555
00:34:54,815 --> 00:34:56,134
Too bad you haven't got
a show ready.

556
00:34:56,335 --> 00:34:58,246
I'll get one.
Sure.

557
00:34:58,455 --> 00:34:59,808
Tony, I've just been thinking.

558
00:35:00,015 --> 00:35:01,243
<i>How would you like
to take over Tropicana?</i>

559
00:35:01,455 --> 00:35:03,286
<i>Tropicana? Tropicana?</i>

560
00:35:03,495 --> 00:35:05,565
Since when have you started
throwing gold-mines away?

561
00:35:05,775 --> 00:35:07,891
Look, Tony, I've got to get away
from this business for a while.

562
00:35:08,095 --> 00:35:09,210
Take a long rest.
Doctor's orders.

563
00:35:09,415 --> 00:35:10,404
You do look terrible.

564
00:35:11,015 --> 00:35:13,654
I do?
Yes.

565
00:35:13,895 --> 00:35:17,934
<i>Look, I'm willing to take a little loss on
Tropicana just so I can get away for a good rest.</i>

566
00:35:18,135 --> 00:35:19,966
Haven't you got Fay Lawrence
under contract to play the lead?

567
00:35:20,175 --> 00:35:21,847
Yes, and she's sensational.

568
00:35:22,055 --> 00:35:23,534
The show was written
for her, you know.

569
00:35:23,735 --> 00:35:25,930
I wouldn't be buried in the same
cemetery with that dame.

570
00:35:26,135 --> 00:35:27,966
It's no deal.
That can be fixed, Tony.

571
00:35:28,175 --> 00:35:29,927
She'd be happy to step out
the minute you took over.

572
00:35:30,135 --> 00:35:31,614
You think she would?
Absolutely.

573
00:35:31,815 --> 00:35:33,965
Every time she hears
your name, she gets sick.

574
00:35:34,175 --> 00:35:36,530
She does?
Tony, she hates you.

575
00:35:36,735 --> 00:35:38,327
Really? Don't you worry
about her hanging on

576
00:35:38,535 --> 00:35:39,854
to the show,
not with your doing it.

577
00:35:40,055 --> 00:35:41,283
Why, she'd pay
for her release.

578
00:35:41,495 --> 00:35:42,723
<i>What'll you take for Tropicana?</i>

579
00:35:42,935 --> 00:35:44,334
Look, I've got $28,000
tied up in it.

580
00:35:44,535 --> 00:35:45,934
I'll tell you what I'll do,
I'll take 20.

581
00:35:46,135 --> 00:35:48,012
Being that you're a sick man,
I'll tell you what I'll do:

582
00:35:48,215 --> 00:35:49,933
I'll give you ten.
I'll tell you what, I'll take it.

583
00:35:50,455 --> 00:35:52,173
Give me the chequebook.

584
00:35:54,255 --> 00:35:55,813
Now the pen.

585
00:35:56,015 --> 00:35:57,414
You're getting the best deal
of your life.

586
00:35:57,615 --> 00:35:59,810
I want to tell you something, this
is the way Tony Ferris does business.

587
00:36:00,055 --> 00:36:03,889
Everything right on
the dotted line.

588
00:36:04,135 --> 00:36:05,887
There you are.
Thanks, Tony.

589
00:36:06,095 --> 00:36:07,210
Now, take good care
of your nerves.

590
00:36:07,415 --> 00:36:08,689
I will. Good luck.
Good luck to you.

591
00:36:08,895 --> 00:36:10,772
You know, Tony, I was just thinking,
better hold back the announcements

592
00:36:10,975 --> 00:36:14,092
until I've had a chance to talk with Fay and
sort of smooth over the rough edges, you know.

593
00:36:14,295 --> 00:36:15,284
Let me handle
the publicity.

594
00:36:15,495 --> 00:36:16,848
It's all yours.
Thanks.

595
00:36:17,055 --> 00:36:18,568
So long, Mouse.

596
00:36:19,935 --> 00:36:21,163
Mouse, we won the battle.

597
00:36:21,375 --> 00:36:24,287
Mark my words, Fay Lawrence will come
back to me crawling on her hands and knees.

598
00:36:24,775 --> 00:36:26,208
Yes, boss, but there's one thing
that's worrying me.

599
00:36:26,415 --> 00:36:27,370
What's that?

600
00:36:27,575 --> 00:36:29,327
How are you gonna cover
this check by tomorrow?

601
00:36:29,535 --> 00:36:31,014
Don't be an idiot.
Tomorrow's Sunday.

602
00:36:31,215 --> 00:36:32,568
Come on.

603
00:36:37,415 --> 00:36:39,167
Well, there you are.

604
00:36:39,375 --> 00:36:41,047
Hello, Fay.
Hello, Forrest.

605
00:36:41,255 --> 00:36:42,529
How are you, boys?

606
00:36:42,775 --> 00:36:46,211
We've been going through those new
choruses of "Can't be bothered" all evening.

607
00:36:46,455 --> 00:36:49,094
Look, gentlemen, I wonder
if you'd please excuse us.

608
00:36:49,295 --> 00:36:51,650
Miss Lawrence and I have some
very important business to discuss.

609
00:36:51,855 --> 00:36:53,413
Thanks for the number, boys.

610
00:36:53,615 --> 00:36:56,766
and we'll wrap it up as a gift
before we give it to our public.

611
00:36:56,975 --> 00:36:58,328
Good night.

612
00:36:58,535 --> 00:37:01,129
Well, I'm glad to see you
in such a happy frame of mind.

613
00:37:01,335 --> 00:37:02,927
Won't you have a drink?
Thanks.

614
00:37:03,135 --> 00:37:04,887
I may need it.

615
00:37:07,495 --> 00:37:09,963
Fay, I have some news for you
that may be a shock.

616
00:37:10,175 --> 00:37:13,963
What is it?
I can't go on with the show.

617
00:37:14,175 --> 00:37:16,370
Oh, is that so?
You what?

618
00:37:16,615 --> 00:37:18,970
As a matter of fact, my backer,
who was to back me, has backed out.

619
00:37:19,175 --> 00:37:20,130
I haven't the money.

620
00:37:20,375 --> 00:37:22,889
However, the show will go on and
I assume that you'll be the star.

621
00:37:23,095 --> 00:37:24,244
But I had to sell the production.

622
00:37:24,455 --> 00:37:26,366
Well, one man's money's
as good as another's.

623
00:37:26,615 --> 00:37:27,684
You may not like your producer.

624
00:37:27,935 --> 00:37:30,449
Oh, I like any producer
who produces.

625
00:37:30,655 --> 00:37:32,008
Who is he?
Tony Ferris.

626
00:37:32,255 --> 00:37:35,167
Tony Ferris.
Why, this is a catastrophe.

627
00:37:35,375 --> 00:37:37,366
I'm sorry, Fay,
I had no other choice.

628
00:37:37,575 --> 00:37:39,054
After all, you two
have had hits before.

629
00:37:39,255 --> 00:37:40,893
Why, you don't know that guy.

630
00:37:41,095 --> 00:37:42,369
Why, this is terrible.

631
00:37:42,575 --> 00:37:45,294
Why, if he'd have been with Washington,
he'd have double-crossed the Delaware.

632
00:37:47,535 --> 00:37:51,574
Hello, may I speak to
the district attorney, please?

633
00:37:51,775 --> 00:37:53,572
Hello, Hubert.

634
00:37:55,615 --> 00:37:57,526
Oh, uh, cancel it.

635
00:37:57,735 --> 00:37:59,453
Oh, I'm so glad
you gentlemen are here.

636
00:37:59,655 --> 00:38:00,610
Glad to see you, Hubert.

637
00:38:00,815 --> 00:38:01,964
How is every little wrinkle?

638
00:38:02,175 --> 00:38:05,087
Thank you. I was just
calling up the district attorney.

639
00:38:05,295 --> 00:38:07,331
District attorney?
What for?

640
00:38:07,535 --> 00:38:12,211
Well, I wanted to confess about
myself and you and Mr Mouse.

641
00:38:12,415 --> 00:38:13,564
Confess what?

642
00:38:13,775 --> 00:38:17,324
About that telephone call
I made to Mr Stanton.

643
00:38:17,535 --> 00:38:19,730
I've felt terrible
about it ever since.

644
00:38:19,935 --> 00:38:21,448
I haven't slept a wink.

645
00:38:21,695 --> 00:38:24,493
I'm a sick man, Mr Ferris.

646
00:38:24,695 --> 00:38:26,572
I never lied in my life.

647
00:38:26,815 --> 00:38:28,646
Hubert, you can forget
about that call.

648
00:38:28,855 --> 00:38:29,810
Forget about it?

649
00:38:30,015 --> 00:38:31,448
Yeah, you never
made it, understand?

650
00:38:31,655 --> 00:38:33,532
Oh, but I did, Mr Ferris.
You remember, you were...

651
00:38:33,735 --> 00:38:34,850
I tell you,
you never made it.

652
00:38:35,095 --> 00:38:36,972
But I did!
You don't remember.

653
00:38:37,175 --> 00:38:39,291
You've got two witnesses
to back you up.

654
00:38:39,495 --> 00:38:42,248
Who's the other witness, boss?
You, you dope.

655
00:38:42,455 --> 00:38:45,731
Do you mean you gentlemen
would really lie for me?

656
00:38:45,935 --> 00:38:47,084
Hubert, we'd die for you.

657
00:38:47,335 --> 00:38:52,125
Oh, you don't know what you've done for
me and for the Bainbridge Foundation.

658
00:38:52,335 --> 00:38:55,771
Why, Mr Stanton could have
sued us for every penny we have.

659
00:38:55,975 --> 00:38:57,533
So what?
Well, how much money can you have?

660
00:38:57,775 --> 00:39:08,925
Well, as of today,
there's $409,000.26

661
00:39:09,175 --> 00:39:11,689
Well, who's rationing
all that sugar?

662
00:39:11,935 --> 00:39:13,527
Pardon me?

663
00:39:13,735 --> 00:39:15,691
I say, who's in charge
of the money?

664
00:39:15,895 --> 00:39:16,930
Oh, I don't know.

665
00:39:17,135 --> 00:39:19,490
I guess I am, as long as
sister Hannah's away.

666
00:39:19,695 --> 00:39:21,845
They couldn't have placed it
in better hands.

667
00:39:22,055 --> 00:39:24,853
I don't know why you men
are so good to me.

668
00:39:25,055 --> 00:39:26,204
You really wanna know?
Yes.

669
00:39:26,415 --> 00:39:30,408
I'll tell you, Hubert, anyone who cares as much about
his niece as you do must be the sweetest guy in the world.

670
00:39:30,615 --> 00:39:32,287
And I'm a pushover for sweet guys.

671
00:39:32,535 --> 00:39:35,527
This is no place for Janey
with her wonderful talent.

672
00:39:35,775 --> 00:39:37,766
Sure, we gotta get her out of here.

673
00:39:37,975 --> 00:39:39,488
You mean it?
Sure.

674
00:39:39,695 --> 00:39:41,287
Why, that's our sacred duty.

675
00:39:41,495 --> 00:39:44,805
You really mean that you'll give
Janey a chance, Mr Ferris?

676
00:39:45,015 --> 00:39:46,084
Hubert, you leave it to me.

677
00:39:46,295 --> 00:39:49,970
I'll fix you, you and Janey, like you've
never been fixed up before in all your life.

678
00:39:50,175 --> 00:39:52,052
Oh, Mr Ferris.

679
00:40:07,135 --> 00:40:09,126
Now you're gonna hear
something terrific.

680
00:40:09,335 --> 00:40:10,006
Yes.
Frank.

681
00:40:10,255 --> 00:40:12,132
Yes, sir.
Is Hazel Scott ready?

682
00:40:12,335 --> 00:40:13,404
It'll take a couple of minutes, boss.

683
00:40:13,615 --> 00:40:14,730
They're still putting
the pianos in place.

684
00:40:14,975 --> 00:40:16,328
I don't want any waits
between numbers.

685
00:40:16,535 --> 00:40:17,604
Get the next one
to follow immediately.

686
00:40:17,855 --> 00:40:20,005
The next will be the "Wabash" number.
We'll need Miss Adair.

687
00:40:21,935 --> 00:40:25,166
Honey, will you get dressed, please?
Right away, Mr Ferris.

688
00:40:25,375 --> 00:40:27,013
Keep your fingers crossed.
Be good.

689
00:40:27,255 --> 00:40:30,850
Good luck, darling.
Thank you, Uncle.

690
00:40:31,335 --> 00:40:33,007
Will you look at this model, please?

691
00:40:33,215 --> 00:40:34,568
Let's see.

692
00:40:34,775 --> 00:40:37,209
No, that won't do, Rennie.
That's not massive enough.

693
00:40:37,415 --> 00:40:38,894
Don't forget, this is
a Tony Ferris production.

694
00:40:39,095 --> 00:40:41,051
I'm only trying to cut
corners a little, Mr Ferris.

695
00:40:41,255 --> 00:40:42,244
Who asked you to cut corners?

